theorem
Th4: ((f is  without+infty & g is  without+infty) implies ( f + g ) is  without+infty)
proof
assume that
A1: f is  without+infty
and
A2: g is  without+infty;
A3: ( dom ( f + g ) ) = ( ( dom f ) /\ ( dom g ) ) by A1,A2,CKB1:1;
(for x being set holds (x in ( dom ( f + g ) ) implies ( ( f + g ) . x ) < ( +infty )))
proof
let x being set;
assume A4: x in ( dom ( f + g ) );
then x in ( dom f ) by A3,XBOOLE_0:def 4;
then A5: ( f . x ) < ( +infty ) by A1,MESFUNC5:11;
x in ( dom g ) by A3,A4,XBOOLE_0:def 4;
then A6: ( g . x ) < ( +infty ) by A2,MESFUNC5:11;
( ( f + g ) . x ) = ( ( f . x ) + ( g . x ) ) by A4,MESFUNC1:def 3;
hence thesis by A5,A6,XXREAL_0:4,XXREAL_3:16;
end;
hence thesis by MESFUNC5:11;
